    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I recommend initializing variables in constructors. That's why they exist: to ensure your objects are constructed (initialized) properly.</p>\n\n<p>Either way will work, and it's a matter of style, but I prefer constructors for member initialization.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 129560,
      "reputation" : 993,
      "user_id" : 328227,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/54a1c9614d1d137191838fe7c901e94f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "mklfarha",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/328227/mklfarha"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1286914852,
    "creation_date" : 1286914852,
    "answer_id" : 3918670,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I think both are correct programming wise,</p>\n\n<p>But i think your first option is more correct in an object oriented way, because in the constructor is when the object is created, and it is when the variable should initialized.</p>\n\n<p>I think it is the \"by the book\" convention, but it is open for discussion.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaBean\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 117125,
      "reputation" : 13809,
      "user_id" : 306855,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 73,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/01482c5fae7fb880a6d7416162e81c05?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Emil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/306855/emil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1286917879,
    "last_edit_date" : 1286917879,
    "creation_date" : 1286917513,
    "answer_id" : 3919021,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>If you initialize in the top or in constructor it doesn't make much difference .But in some case initializing in constructor makes sense.</p>\n\n<pre><code>class String\n{\n    char[] arr/*=char [20]*/; //Here initializing char[] over here will not make sense.\n    String()\n    {\n        this.arr=new char[0];\n    }\n    String(char[] arr)\n    {\n        this.arr=arr;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>So depending on the situation sometime you will have to initialize in the top and sometimes in a constructor. </p>\n\n<p>FYI other option's for initialization without using a constructor :</p>\n\n<pre><code>class Foo\n{\n    int i;\n    static int k;\n\n    //instance initializer block\n    {\n        //run's every time a new object is created\n        i=20;\n    }\n\n    //static initializer block\n    static{\n        //run's only one time when the class is loaded\n        k=18;\n    }    \n} \n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 217833,
      "reputation" : 5027,
      "user_id" : 473831,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/734f6e8c4330aeecac9c0295e662f1a4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "kasgoku",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/473831/kasgoku"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1286918405,
    "creation_date" : 1286918405,
    "answer_id" : 3919119,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Both the options can be correct depending on your situation.</p>\n\n<p>A very simple example would be: If you have multiple constructors all of which initialize the variable the same way(int x=2 for each one of them). It makes sense to initialize the variable at declaration to avoid redundancy.</p>\n\n<p>It also makes sense to consider final variables in such a situation. If you know what value a final variable will have at declaration, it makes sense to initialize it outside the constructors. However, if you want the users of your class to initialize the final variable through a constructor, delay the initialization until the constructor.</p>\n"
  }, {
