    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 18868,
      "reputation" : 84028,
      "user_id" : 43681,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 70,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6c2dd6a39d3f38f1bb47a8c1fe8325e2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "sleske",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/43681/sleske"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 263,
    "last_activity_date" : 1286919298,
    "creation_date" : 1286919298,
    "answer_id" : 3919225,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I find the second style (declaration + initialization in one go) superior. Reasons:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>It makes it clear at a glance how the variable is initialized. Typically, when reading a program and coming across a variable, you'll first go to its declaration (often automatic in IDEs). With style 2, you see the default value right away. With style 1, you need to look at the constructor as well.</li>\n<li>If you have more than one constructor, you don't have to repeat the initializations (and you cannot forget them).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Of course, if the initialization value is different in different constructors (or even calculated in the constructor), you must do it in the constructor.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 134312,
      "reputation" : 11682,
      "user_id" : 336355,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5411154938b6403b2c97a458ea1ab9fb?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ishtar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/336355/ishtar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1286922826,
    "creation_date" : 1286922826,
    "answer_id" : 3919585,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I would say, it depends on the <em>default</em>. For example</p>\n\n<pre><code>public Bar\n{\n  ArrayList&lt;Foo&gt; foos;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I would make a <code>new ArrayList</code> outside of the constructor, if I always assume <code>foos</code> can not be null. If <code>Bar</code> is a valid object, not caring if <code>foos</code> is null or not, I would put it in the constructor. </p>\n\n<p>You might disagree and say that it's the constructors job to put the object in a valid state. However, if clearly <em>all</em> the constructors should do exactly the same thing(initialize <code>foos</code>), why duplicate that code?</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 11589053,
        "reputation" : 91,
        "user_id" : 8490102,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/sg4j2.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Kaiser Keister",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8490102/kaiser-keister"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1524708867,
      "post_id" : 13310667,
      "comment_id" : 87083810,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Even better than a no-arg constructor: an instance initializer block. If you&#39;re concerned about adding logic later, you could initialize everything in an instance initializer block so you don&#39;t have to call <code>this()</code> in your constructors."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1598029,
        "reputation" : 509,
        "user_id" : 1479668,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 36,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ddb3d0670b9ea092ac44aaa8f5a3ba6d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "magulla",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1479668/magulla"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1539822353,
      "post_id" : 13310667,
      "comment_id" : 92644756,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "if construction of object requires logic -then it should be done in factory method, not in constructor."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 4777867,
        "reputation" : 351,
        "user_id" : 3860494,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 60,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/99b2a73bf798439408865b94628d0dec?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Cromm",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3860494/cromm"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 1598029,
        "reputation" : 509,
        "user_id" : 1479668,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 36,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ddb3d0670b9ea092ac44aaa8f5a3ba6d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "magulla",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1479668/magulla"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1585143465,
      "post_id" : 13310667,
      "comment_id" : 107658957,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@magulla not necessarily, if the object holds and enforce its rules, you can add logic in the constructor. Example, let&#39;s say a object &quot;Temperature&quot;, where the constructor takes a float &quot;value&quot; and an enum &quot;tempScale&quot;, where you check in the constructor that if TempScale = TempScale.Celsius and value &lt; −273,15 then, you raise an exception, or automatically set the value to −273,15... Same for value &lt; −459,67 and tempScale = Fahrenheit. You definitly don&#39;t need a factory for this."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1598029,
        "reputation" : 509,
        "user_id" : 1479668,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 36,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ddb3d0670b9ea092ac44aaa8f5a3ba6d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "magulla",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1479668/magulla"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 4777867,
        "reputation" : 351,
        "user_id" : 3860494,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 60,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/99b2a73bf798439408865b94628d0dec?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Cromm",
