      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1594820940,
      "post_id" : 13310667,
      "comment_id" : 111260921,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@Cromm yes, you can do that, but my point is that it is not a good practice, in my opinion: - if  you have a logic, that is not related to actual construction, - if your logic can cause an exception, then you are opening a door to a potential usage of incomplete object reference."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 948242,
        "reputation" : 399,
        "user_id" : 975019,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 60,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4d66769aebb8728dd1249b94018a7580?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Skystrider",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/975019/skystrider"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1691095782,
      "post_id" : 13310667,
      "comment_id" : 135449398,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Use Factories and POJOs for clean design. One class represents the structure of an object (POJO) and another class like Factory or helper or consumer or controller or anything that is smart and understands how to do things can manipulate the data of the POJO. Factories specifically for initializing the POJO which can include logic/conditions or configured data."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2028137,
      "reputation" : 369,
      "user_id" : 1812588,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6cec2bf18e7791b4b20753159306a337?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Joseph Cozad",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1812588/joseph-cozad"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 36,
    "last_activity_date" : 1352474096,
    "creation_date" : 1352474096,
    "answer_id" : 13310667,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have the practice (habit) of almost always initializing in the contructor for two reasons, one in my opinion it adds to readablitiy (cleaner), and two there is more logic control in the constructor than in one line. Even if initially the instance variable doesn't require logic, having it in the constructor gives more flexibility to add logic in the future if needed.</p>\n\n<p>As to the concern mentioned above about multiple constructors, that's easily solved by having one no-arg constructor that initializes all the instance variables that are initilized the same for all constructors and then each constructor calls this() at the first line. That solves your reduncancy issues.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 26747,
      "reputation" : 20445,
      "user_id" : 69875,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/595c6bb51e00b5dcb491c8648c0cc829?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Jonathan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/69875/jonathan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1374655795,
    "creation_date" : 1374655795,
    "answer_id" : 17829249,
    "question_id" : 3918578,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It can depend on <em>what</em> your are initialising, for example you cannot just use field initialisation if a checked exception is involved. For example, the following:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Foo {\n    FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(\"/tmp\"); // throws FileNotFoundException\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Will cause a compile-time error unless you also include a constructor declaring that checked exception, or extend a superclass which does, e.g.:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public Foo() throws FileNotFoundException {} \n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
